    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-05-05T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-05-05T00:00:00-05:00" n="144"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d144">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">837.51/2783</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum Handed to the Cuban Ambassador</hi> (<persName
                        type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Concheso</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">by the Under Secretary of State</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Welles</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-05-05">May 5,
                            1941</date>.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Following conversations over the past several months between Cuban authorities
                    and officials of the United States Government, the Export-Import Bank has
                    established a credit of $25,000,000 to be availed of by the Cuban Government to
                    finance the purchase of materials, equipment and services required in the
                    Republic of Cuba for agricultural development and diversification and public or
                    other useful works projects, including irrigation systems, highways, and
                    sanitation works throughout the Island of Cuba.</p>
                <p>This commitment, which was made by the Executive Committee of the Export-Import
                    Bank on May 1, is a further step forward in the development of a program of
                    economic collaboration between Cuba and the United States.</p>
                <p>Funds will be advanced under this credit as individual projects are studied and
                    approved by the appropriate authorities of the two Governments. The precise
                    terms of the arrangement will be worked out by representatives of the Cuban
                    Government and the Bank.</p>
            </div>
